## Commands

```bash
docker compose up -d --build                                  # full stack (≤60s)
docker compose --profile multinode up -d --build              # second Kong node on :8001 (independent in-process caches)
docker compose down -v                                        # tear down + reset

# Java (per service)
./mvnw -pl services/ms-auth test                              # unit + integration (Testcontainers)
./mvnw -pl services/ms-auth spring-boot:run                   # local run (without Compose)

# Kong plugin
docker compose exec kong /usr/local/bin/pongo run             # busted suite via kong-pongo

# E2E + load
npx newman run tests/newman/auth-trust-gateway.postman_collection.json \
  -e tests/newman/env.poc.postman_environment.json --bail
k6 run tests/k6/load-authenticated-route.js \
  --env BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000 --env USERNAME=alice --env PASSWORD=alice
bash tests/k6/chaos-msauth-down.sh
```

## Code Style

- **Java**: Java 25 features OK (records, pattern matching, virtual threads). Prefer immutable DTOs (`record`). Use Spring `@HttpExchange` for outbound HTTP. Logback JSON via `logstash-logback-encoder`. No `RestTemplate` in new code.
- **Lua plugin**: Local `require` at top of file. No globals. Use `kong.log.warn/err/info` (never `print`). All cache keys prefixed with `jwks:<issuer>:`. Never log token contents.
- **YAML / Compose**: `expose:` (not `ports:`) for everything except Kong proxy port `8000`. Healthchecks on every service.
- **Tests**: Mirror `CA-NNN` IDs from spec in test names so traceability is greppable (`CA-006_spoofed_xuserid_is_overwritten`).

## Architectural Invariants (do NOT violate)

- The end client never reaches Keycloak directly. `keycloak` service has **no** `ports:` mapping (FR-015 / SC-010).
- Kong **always** runs `jwt-keycloak-validator` with `strip_client_headers: true` on every protected route (FR-010 / SC-005).
- Microservices downstream **never** validate JWTs themselves. They trust `X-User-Id` from Kong only (FR-014).
- The Kong plugin **never** calls Keycloak directly — only `http://ms-auth:8080/auth/jwks` (FR-005).

